Introduction¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.
Certain columns, like cast and genres, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters.
There are some odd characters in the cast column. Dont worry about cleaning them. You can leave them as is.
The final two columns ending with _adj show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

Dataset Description¶

Bellow you will findout a CSV file, that is the main file we will analize in this present dataset.

Question(s) for Analysis in the present DataSet¶

  • Which genres are most popular from year to year?

  • Which movies had lowest and largest price(budget)?

  • What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

  • Which movie had the highest or lowest Profit?

  • Which year had the highest release of movies?

  • Which Movie had longest and shortest runtime?

Raw Obsevations from the Dataset¶

I. The present dataset has no unit of currency is mentioned. In this way I will take it as metical (MZN) as it is the coin name used in my country;

II. We cannot directly conculed the popularity of the movies based on the average vote count, because vote_count is different for all the movies;

III. I found 3 important column bellow: budget, revenue and popularity, that will be useful for this analysis and we are going to calculate the profit extract the revenue from the budget column;

IV. We need to handle missing values from budget and revenue column before the calculation;

I found too, the follow important columns :director, original_title & cast, that have useful information about the movies. release_date, and release_year columns also important. And we need the convert the release_date column to pandas DateTime object;

VI. The follow columns: (homepage, tagline, keywords, overview, vote_average, budget_adj, revenue_adj) have unuseful information about the movies for this analysis, so these columns could be deleted.

In [44]:
def getMath(column):
    #Getting highest earned profit
    high= fetch[column].idxmax()
    high_details=ps.DataFrame(fetch.loc[high])
    
    #Getting lowest earned profit
    low= fetch[column].idxmin()
    low_details=ps.DataFrame(fetch.loc[low])
    
    #Merging data in one place
    info=ps.concat([high_details, low_details], axis=1)
    
    return info

In [77]:
#We can fetch the best 5 position instead of showing the lowest and high
def getTop5(column,size=5):
    fetch_sorted = ps.DataFrame(fetch[column].sort_values(ascending=False))[:size]
    fetch_sorted['original_title'] = fetch['original_title']
    plot.figure(figsize=(12,6))
    #Calculate the avarage
    avg = np.mean(fetch[column])   
    sb.barplot(x=column, y='original_title', data=fetch_sorted, label=column)
    plot.axvline(avg, color='k', linestyle='--', label='mean')
    if (column == 'profit' or column == 'budget' or column == 'revenue'):
        plot.xlabel(column.capitalize() + ' (MZN - Metical)')
    else:
        plot.xlabel(column.capitalize())
    plot.ylabel('')
    plot.title('Top 5 Movies in: ' + column.capitalize())
    plot.legend()
In [78]:
getTop5('profit')

Conclusions¶

After making an analysis on this date set, it was possible to verify the following situations solved:

  • Movies can succeed if her genres is Action, Adventure, Thriller, Comedy, Drama;
  • Documentary Genre is a movie type that can take a longest run time;
  • Based on the dataset result, the movie made by James Cameron named AVATAR earned the highest profit in all, making over 2.5B in profit;

I had a limitation to make the relationship between the budget used on production and its popularity.
